To achieve the expected output and remove entries with `null` values from your `LinkedListMultimap`, you can filter out the `null` values while printing the entries. Here&#39;s how you can do it:

```java
import com.google.common.collect.LinkedListMultimap;
import com.google.common.collect.Multimap;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Multimap&lt;String, String&gt; data = LinkedListMultimap.create();
        data.put(&quot;NAME&quot;, getName());
        data.put(&quot;AGE&quot;, getAge());
        data.put(&quot;DEPARTMENT&quot;, getDepartment());

        data.entries().stream()
            .filter(entry -&gt; entry.getValue() != null)
            .forEach(entry -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;[&quot; + entry.getKey() + &quot;]&quot; + &quot; &quot; + entry.getValue()));
    }

    // Your getName, getAge, and getDepartment methods here

}
```

In this code, we use the `entries()` method of the `Multimap` to get all the key-value pairs as a collection of `Map.Entry` objects. Then, we stream over these entries, filtering out those where the value is not `null`, and print the remaining entries.

This way, you&#39;ll get the expected output without any entries containing `null` values.

